div.div:
Whatever happens in this circle needs to retain information.
Many transformations can preserve information for one step, but when we talk about life long updating of the brain state, there are not much choice.
With a very long sequence of updating, even for unitary transformation, it would already introduced lots of numerical errors, not to mention if the update is stochastic.
The idea of gradient descent with random minibatches revisits the information via random sampling. Randomization & amortization are very powerful ideas, but not the right tool if our goal is to preserve information.
The above said, there are a few things that are quite reliable in preserving information,
1. Appending each piece of observation in a list, this is photo copy memory, not so useful for making predictions, but super accurate in storing information. The KV cache in the transformer architecture makes past information more accurately stored.
2. Counting, or more broadly, additive statistics. The idea is that the old information should be kept as it is, preferably gets a identity mapping in the update.
